As funes de reshape (pivotagem)

  • Formato long
library(tidyverse)

# Toy data
cases <- tribble(
  ~Country, ~"2011", ~"2012", ~"2013",
      "FR",    7000,    6900,    7000,
      "DE",    5800,    6000,    6200,
      "US",   15000,   14000,   13000
)

cases_long <- pivot_longer(cases, cols = 2:4, names_to = "ano", values_to = "pop")

cases_long <- pivot_longer(cases, cols = `2011`:`2013`, names_to = "ano", values_to = "pop")

cases_long <- pivot_longer(cases, cols = starts_with("20"), names_to = "ano", values_to = "pop")
  • Formato wider

E se quisessemos voltar os dados ao formato original?

pivot_wider(cases_long, names_from = ano, values_from = pop)
## # A tibble: 3  4
##   Country `2011` `2012` `2013`
##   <chr>    <dbl>  <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 FR        7000   6900   7000
## 2 DE        5800   6000   6200
## 3 US       15000  14000  13000
  • Helper functions separate e unite

Queremos fazer uma tabela: city X size

pollution <- tribble(
       ~city, ~amount,
  "New York_large",      23,
  "New York_small",      14,
    "London_large",      22,
    "London_small",      16,
   "Beijing_large",     121,
   "Beijing_small",     56
)

pollution %>% separate(city, sep = "_", into = c("city", "size"))
## # A tibble: 6  3
##   city     size  amount
##   <chr>    <chr>  <dbl>
## 1 New York large     23
## 2 New York small     14
## 3 London   large     22
## 4 London   small     16
## 5 Beijing  large    121
## 6 Beijing  small     56
pollution %>% 
  separate(city, sep = "_", into = c("city", "size")) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = size, values_from = amount)
## # A tibble: 3  3
##   city     large small
##   <chr>    <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 New York    23    14
## 2 London      22    16
## 3 Beijing    121    56

E se quisssemos fazer o contrrio

pollution2 <- pollution %>% separate(city, sep = "_", into = c("city", "size"))

pollution2 %>% unite(col = "city", city, size, sep = "_" )
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   city           amount
##   <chr>           <dbl>
## 1 New York_large     23
## 2 New York_small     14
## 3 London_large       22
## 4 London_small       16
## 5 Beijing_large     121
## 6 Beijing_small      56

Juntando bases: o _join do dplyr

https://www.curso-r.com/material/manipulacao/

https://r4ds.had.co.nz/relational-data.html#understanding-joins

x <- tribble(
  ~key, ~val_x,
     1, "x1",
     2, "x2",
     3, "x3"
)
y <- tribble(
  ~key, ~val_y,
     1, "y1",
     2, "y2",
     4, "y3"
)

left_join(x, y, by = "key")
## # A tibble: 3  3
##     key val_x val_y
##   <dbl> <chr> <chr>
## 1     1 x1    y1   
## 2     2 x2    y2   
## 3     3 x3    <NA>
right_join(x, y, by = "key")
## # A tibble: 3  3
##     key val_x val_y
##   <dbl> <chr> <chr>
## 1     1 x1    y1   
## 2     2 x2    y2   
## 3     4 <NA>  y3
full_join(x, y, by = "key")
## # A tibble: 4  3
##     key val_x val_y
##   <dbl> <chr> <chr>
## 1     1 x1    y1   
## 2     2 x2    y2   
## 3     3 x3    <NA> 
## 4     4 <NA>  y3
  • E se as variveis key tivessem nomes diferentes
x <- tribble(
  ~id, ~val_x,
     1, "x1",
     2, "x2",
     3, "x3"
)
y <- tribble(
  ~key, ~val_y,
     1, "y1",
     2, "y2",
     4, "y3"
)

left_join(x, y, by = c("id"="key"))
## # A tibble: 3  3
##      id val_x val_y
##   <dbl> <chr> <chr>
## 1     1 x1    y1   
## 2     2 x2    y2   
## 3     3 x3    <NA>
  • E se tivssemos identificadores duplicadas ?

library(scales)

enem %>% 
  select(TP_SEXO, NU_NOTA_CN:NU_NOTA_MT) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = NU_NOTA_CN:NU_NOTA_MT, 
    names_to = "enem",
    values_to = "escr_tri"
    ) %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = escr_tri, fill = enem)) +
    geom_density(alpha = .50) +
    scale_fill_grey() +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::breaks_width(100)) +
    facet_wrap(~TP_SEXO, ncol = 1)
